article.headline: Wright leads Boilermakers with 15 points
article.linkText: Wright, No. 7 Purdue pass easy test vs. Panthers
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Winning was the No. 1 goal for the Purdue
Boilermakers in Friday night's season opener. Getting through it
without having their players break a heavy sweat could have been
No. 2.

	   Shereka Wright scored 15 points as the seventh-ranked
Boilermakers defeated Wisconsin-Milwaukee 82-59 while resting
Wright and the rest of the starters for much of the second half.

	   Wright played a total of 14 minutes, and none of her teammates
played more than 16.

	   "It's good to get the first one under our belt,'' Purdue coach
Kristy Curry said. "I was happy with the way we played in the
first half, but there are some areas where we have to get better.''

	   The Panthers fell victim to Purdue's man-to-man defense in the
first half, when Wisconsin-Milwaukee committed 13 turnovers. Five
came on steals by Purdue guard Erica Valek.

	   Maria Viall led the Panthers with 21 points on 10-of-18
shooting; she also blocked six shots.

	   Jessica Wilhite, the outside half of the Panthers' one-two
punch, was stifled by Valek and Purdue's other quick guard, Beth
Jones. Wilhite scored just nine points -- on three 3-pointers.

	   "We've got to get Jess more open looks than we got her
tonight,'' Panthers coach Sandy Botham said. "When she did get
some open looks (in the second half), she looked almost
surprised.''

	   Botham praised Viall for her performance in a matchup with
Purdue's 6-foot-5 center Mary Jo Noon, who averaged 13.1 points and
5.4 rebounds a game last season. Noon scored four points on 1-for-7
shooting and had four rebounds and two blocks.

	   "Maria has played against big players before, and she's played
in big games,'' Botham said. "We struggled getting her the ball at
times, but when she got it, she knew what to do with it.''
